HBV-Liver-Fibrosis

This repository provides an open-source XGBoost-based model for multiclass liver fibrosis staging among individuals with previous or current hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection. The model was developed using routinely available clinical variables and predicts the probability of four fibrosis stages: F0, F1, F2, and F3. The final predicted fibrosis stage is determined by the class with the highest predicted probability.

To use the model, users should first download this repository to their local computer. The repository contains the trained XGBoost model, the required feature list, a background dataset for SHAP interpretation, an input template, and the prediction script. The recommended folder structure is shown below:
HBV-Liver-Fibrosis/
├── model/
│   ├── xgboost_fibrosis_model.rds
│   ├── feature_names.rds
│   └── background_data.rds
├── input/
│   └── input_template.csv
├── results/
├── predict.R
└── README.md

Users should prepare the input data using the template file input/input_template.csv. Each row represents one participant, and multiple participants can be analyzed simultaneously. The input file must contain the following variables: Patient_ID, GNRI, BMI, NPAR, ALB, TC, CRP, Creatinine, WtHR, HDL, and age.

After completing the input file, users can open R or RStudio, set the working directory to the repository folder, and run the following code:
# Set working directory to the repository folder
# setwd("path/to/HBV-Liver-Fibrosis")

# Load required packages
library(dplyr)
library(mlr3)
library(mlr3learners)

# Load trained model and feature names
model <- readRDS("model/xgboost_fibrosis_model.rds")
feature_names <- readRDS("model/feature_names.rds")

# Read input data
input_data <- read.csv("input/input_template.csv")

# Check whether all required variables are included
missing_features <- setdiff(feature_names, colnames(input_data))

if (length(missing_features) > 0) {
  stop(
    paste(
      "The following required variables are missing:",
      paste(missing_features, collapse = ", ")
    )
  )
}

# Keep only required predictors
newdata <- input_data %>%
  select(all_of(feature_names))

# Generate predictions
pred <- model$predict_newdata(newdata)

# Extract predicted probabilities
prob_result <- as.data.frame(pred$prob)

# Add patient ID and final predicted stage
prediction_result <- cbind(
  Patient_ID = input_data$Patient_ID,
  prob_result,
  Predicted_stage = pred$response
)

# Save prediction results
dir.create("results", showWarnings = FALSE)

write.csv(
  prediction_result,
  file = "results/fibrosis_prediction_results.csv",
  row.names = FALSE
)

# Show results
prediction_result



The output file will be saved as results/fibrosis_prediction_results.csv. This file includes the predicted probabilities for F0, F1, F2, and F3, as well as the final predicted fibrosis stage for each participant.

For individualized model interpretation, SHAP analysis can be used to estimate the contribution of each clinical variable to the predicted fibrosis stage. The following code provides an example of SHAP-based interpretation for the input participants:

library(kernelshap)
library(shapviz)
library(ggplot2)

# Load background data for SHAP calculation
background_data <- readRDS("model/background_data.rds")

# Define prediction function for multiclass probability output
pred_fun <- function(object, newdata) {
  pred <- object$predict_newdata(as.data.frame(newdata))
  as.data.frame(pred$prob)
}

# Calculate SHAP values
ks <- kernelshap(
  object = model,
  X = newdata,
  bg_X = background_data,
  pred_fun = pred_fun
)

# Convert to shapviz object
sv <- shapviz(ks)

# Plot SHAP summary for each fibrosis stage
p_F0 <- sv_importance(sv[["0"]], kind = "bar", max_display = 10) +
  ggtitle("SHAP Explanation: F0")

p_F1 <- sv_importance(sv[["1"]], kind = "bar", max_display = 10) +
  ggtitle("SHAP Explanation: F1")

p_F2 <- sv_importance(sv[["2"]], kind = "bar", max_display = 10) +
  ggtitle("SHAP Explanation: F2")

p_F3 <- sv_importance(sv[["3"]], kind = "bar", max_display = 10) +
  ggtitle("SHAP Explanation: F3")

# Save SHAP plots
ggsave("results/SHAP_F0.png", p_F0, width = 6, height = 5, dpi = 300)
ggsave("results/SHAP_F1.png", p_F1, width = 6, height = 5, dpi = 300)
ggsave("results/SHAP_F2.png", p_F2, width = 6, height = 5, dpi = 300)
ggsave("results/SHAP_F3.png", p_F3, width = 6, height = 5, dpi = 300)

The SHAP plots show which variables contributed most strongly to each fibrosis-stage prediction. Positive SHAP values indicate that a variable increases the predicted probability of a given fibrosis stage, whereas negative SHAP values indicate that a variable decreases that probability.

This model is intended for research use and clinical decision-support exploration. It should not replace clinical judgment, transient elastography, laboratory evaluation, or specialist assessment. Users are encouraged to perform external validation before applying the model in independent clinical settings.
